Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Haiti. The Haitian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
If you live in the UK and are currently travelling abroad, you are strongly advised to return now, where and while there are still commercial routes available. Many airlines are suspending flights and major airports are closing, preventing flights from leaving.
Local measures
On 19 March the Haitian President announced a national state of emergency and detailed measures aimed at tackling the spread of the Coronavirus. We strongly advise all British citizens in Haiti to follow the measures set out by President Moise in full. Key measures include:
A curfew between 2000 and 0500, effective from Friday 20 March;
Citizens to stay at home and limit their movements to essential movements only;
Schools, universities and factories and places of worship to close until further notice;
A ban on all events/meetings of more than 10 people
Entry and borders
President Mo√Øse also announced that, starting at midnight on March 20, all ports, airports, and borders would be closed with the exception of transportation of merchandise, and the captains and the pilots of cargo vessels/planes.
This exclusion will not apply to: Haitian citizens and permanent residents or their immediate families, or diplomats.
Further information
Information is available from the Ministry of Health (Ministere de la Sante publique et de la Population (in French and Kreyol).
You should comply with any screening or quarantine requirements imposed by the Haitian authorities.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
